Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you donâ€™t have symptoms.

Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Eswatini. The Eswatini authorities have introduced a number of measures to limit the spread of the virus.
Travel restrictions and borders
From 16 April, there will be a 21 day extension to the partial lock down that was introduced on Friday 27 March. Border restrictions will continue to be imposed, limiting entry and exit to Eswatini to citizens and residents only. Returning residents will be subjected to mandatory 14- day quarantine in designated locations, apart from those permitted to self-isolate.
British Nationals in Eswatini, particularly those who have been in a coronavirus affected country (including the UK) in the past 20 days, should be aware that it is not possible to leave Eswatini by road into South Africa after 20 March without a visa. The last Airlink flight left Eswatini on 26 March. It is no longer be possible to leave Eswatini by commercial aircraft until further notice. South African airspace closed to commercial aircraft as of midnight 26 March. Follow our travel advice for South Africa
You should comply with any additional screening measures put in place by the authorities. Keep up to date with information from your tour operator, transport or accommodation provider on the impact of any existing travel plans.
If you need further information about entry requirements, contact the local immigration authorities or the nearest Eswatini High Commission. You should also check with your airline or travel company for the latest information.
Local measures
From 16 April, there will be a 21 day extension to the partial lock down in Eswatini that was introduced on Friday 27 March. The army and police will continue to be deployed to ensure compliance with the lockdown measures introduced:
Movements outside of the home perimeter will be restricted, with exception of acquiring essential services such as healthcare, food and banking services.
Non-essential travel between towns will be prohibited.
Public transport will only operate for essential movements.
Food outlets and banks will be restricted to 20 people.
All bars and off licenses will be closed
Public gatherings of more than 20 people will be prohibited.
Further information
Further information on coronavirus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
You can find more information about cases in Eswatini on the TravelHealthPro page.
